In TypeScript, you can use type predicates to communicate to the type system that you know a value will only be one of a possible set of types.

Here is an example:

```typescript
let myValue: string | null;

// ... some code that determines the actual type of myValue

if (/* some condition */) {
  myValue = /* string expression */;
} else {
  myValue = null;
}
```

In this case, TypeScript infers that `myValue` is a `string` because it's assigned a `string` expression. If the condition is not met, `myValue` is `null`, and TypeScript still considers `myValue` to be a `string`, even though in theory it could also be `null`.

If you want to make this explicit, you can use a type predicate:

```typescript
let myValue: string | null;

// ... some code that determines the actual type of myValue

if (/* some condition */) {
  myValue = /* string expression */;
} else {
  myValue = null;
}

if (typeof myValue === 'string') {
  myValue: string;
  // ...
}
```

The `myValue: string` statement inside the `if` block is a type predicate. It tells TypeScript that `myValue` is a `string`, even though in theory it could also be `null`. TypeScript will ensure at compile-time that the `myValue` really is a `string` within this block, and will raise an error if it is not.

